","1322":"1322","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Wodeton, Isle of Wight, England":"Isle of Wight, England, United Kingdom","Malton, York, England":"Malton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Insula","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician: habitational name from any of the places called Insua, meaning ‘island, peninsula (of a river or of the sea), land by a river’, from Latin <i>insula</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Insula was born about 1280, in Isle of Wight, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John de Insula. She married Sir John de Eure I. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1280–":"umbes 1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1275–1322":"1275–1322","1303–1367":"1303–1367","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1305":"1305","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1303":"13